<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Correlation Coefficient</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The correlation coefficient, sometimes also called the cross-correlation co=
efficient, Pearson correlation coefficient (PCC), Pearson's <img src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/CorrelationCoefficient/Inline1.=
svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" borde=
r=3D"0" width=3D"7" height=3D"21" alt=3D"r">, the Perason product-moment co=
rrelation coefficient (PPMCC),
 or the bivariate correlation, is a quantity that gives the quality of a <a=
 href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/LeastSquaresFitting.html">least
 squares fitting</a> to the original data. To define the correlation coeffi=
cient,
 first consider the sum of squared values <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wol=
fram.com/images/equations/CorrelationCoefficient/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inli=
neformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"3=
0" height=3D"22" alt=3D"ss_(xx)">, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/images/equations/CorrelationCoefficient/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformu=
la" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"31" heig=
ht=3D"24" alt=3D"ss_(xy)">, and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/i=
mages/equations/CorrelationCoefficient/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula"=
 style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"32" height=
=3D"24" alt=3D"ss_(yy)"> of a set of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.=
com/images/equations/CorrelationCoefficient/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlinefor=
mula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" hei=
ght=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> data points <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com=
/images/equations/CorrelationCoefficient/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformul=
a" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"48" heigh=
t=3D"22" alt=3D"(x_i,y_i)"> about their respective means,
</p>
